@node Background "Background"
My third project in Amiga E, this program was born because of a perceived
lack of function-laden tagline generation utilities at a reasonable price.
It originally started as an ARexx script called RexxTag (and RexxTagII, the
functionality of both programs has been integrated into this package) and
has developed into a fast, efficient tool for use by FidoNet points (and
others).
@endnode

@node Features "Features"
AmigaETag contains a number of useful features, listed below.

    @{" Compatibility " link Compatibility}
    @{" Speed " link Speed}
    @{" Functionality " link Functionality}
@endnode

@node Compatibility "Compatibility"
o AmigaETag is fully Commodore Style Guide compliant
o Default program behavior is identical to that of Nico François' fantastic
  point package, Spot
o Works with Spot format tag files without modification
o Line-style tag files can be easily converted to Spot format with the
  included ConvertTag utility
o Compatible with all known point software (tested with Spot, April, Foozle,
  MS-QWiK, and C-Net BBS)
@endnode

@node Speed "Speed"
o Compares very favorably to all known external tagline programs,
  particularly with indexing enabled
@endnode

@node Functionality "Functionality"
o Command-line specification of both tag file and edit file names for
  maximum flexibility
o Option to output taglines to the console for use in redirection or pipes
o Auto-detects the number of taglines available or allows the user to
  specify how many exist for greater speed without need to edit the tag file
o Optional user-defined tag prefix for easy customization
o Allows the use of a predefined seed for predictable tagline generation
o Supports the selection of a specific tagline instead of a randomly-chosen
  one
o Easily allows multi-line taglines to be used via the "%%" separator (used
  by Spot)
o Buffered I/O streams are used for extremely fast and efficient tagline
  additions
o Taglines are automatically stripped from edited messages (or left intact
  via keyword)
@endnode

@node Requirements "Requirements"
o Any Amiga running AmigaDOS 2.04 (V37) or greater
o A file containing from 1 to infinite (theoretical) taglines to be
  randomly appended to the end of messages
@endnode

